,"shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-19T04:52:36.882761Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. Parse Genres (for Content-Based Filtering)\n(starter code)\n\nTurns the string of genres into a matrix of 1s and 0s, which preps for content-based filtering.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Parse genres into a multi-hot encoded DataFrame\nall_genres = set()\nfor genres_str in movies_df['genres']:\n    if genres_str != '(no genres listed)':\n        all_genres.update(genres_str.split('|'))\n\nall_genres = sorted(all_genres)\nprint(f\"All genres ({len(all_genres)}): {all_genres}\")\n\n# Create genre feature matrix\ngenre_matrix = pd.DataFrame(0, index=movies_df['movieId'], columns=all_genres)\nfor _, row in movies_df.iterrows():\n    if row['genres'] != '(no genres listed)':\n        for genre in row['genres'].split('|'):\n            genre_matrix.loc[row['movieId'], genre] = 1\n\nprint(f\"\\nGenre feature matrix shape: {genre_matrix.shape}\")\nprint(genre_matrix.head())","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-19T04:52:36.886432Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-19T04:52:36.887207Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-19T04:52:38.904132Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-19T04:52:36.887176Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-19T04:52:38.903155Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 5. Train/Test Split\n(starter code)\n\nTakes 20% of EACH user's rating and hides them to use as the test set to test the model.\nThe remaining 80% is used to train the model. We will see if the model can guess the hidden 20% correctly.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Split ratings into train and test sets\n# Strategy: For each user, hold out 20% of their ratings for testing\n\ntrain_data = []\ntest_data = []\n\nfor user_id, user_ratings in small_df.groupby('userId'):\n    if (len(user_ratings) < 2) :\n        # Since using small df, some users only have 1 rating\n        # 1 rating cannot be split into 2, so we put it into training\n        train_data.append(user_ratings)\n    else:\n        user_train, user_test = train_test_split(\n            user_ratings, test_size=0.2, random_state=42\n        )\n        train_data.append(user_train)\n        test_data.append(user_test)\n\ntrain_df = pd.concat(train_data).reset_index(drop=True)\ntest_df = pd.concat(test_data).reset_index(drop=True)\n\nprint(f\"Training ratings: {len(train_df):,}\")\nprint(f\"Test ratings: {len(test_df):,}\")\nprint(f\"Train users: {train_df['userId'].nunique()}, Test users: {test_df['userId'].nunique()}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-19T04:52:38.905691Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-19T04:52:38.905974Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.676239Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-19T04:52:38.90595Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.675341Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"genre_df = movies_df[[\"movieId\", \"title\", \"genres\"]].copy()\ngenre_df[\"genre_set\"] = genre_df[\"genres\"].apply(lambda x: set(x.split(\"|\")))\n\ngenre_dummies = movies_df[\"genres\"].str.get_dummies(sep=\"|\")\ngenre_df_onehot = genre_dummies.set_index(movies_df[\"movieId\"])","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.677343Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.677695Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.803536Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.677659Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.802546Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 6. Matrix Factorization\n(our code)\n\nThis Matrix Factorization is trained with the Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) by using learned latent factor vectors for users and movies to predict rating.\n\nWe follow the interaction model formula: rating = mu + b_u + b_i + p_u · q_i\n* mu = global mean (baseline reference)\n* b_u = user bias\n* b_i = item bias\n* p_u = latent factor for user's taste\n* q_i = latent factor for item's property\n\nRecommendations are generated by ranking predicted ratings for unseen movies.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)** is an optimization algorithm that aims to find the global minimum of the error function, essentially minimizing the loss.\nThe gradient tells us which direction is downhill (toward the minimum), and the descent takes a step in that direction.\n\n### Process\n1. Fill the two matrices (user and item) with small, random values (np.random.normal)\n2. Predict the rating for a movie by calculating the dot product between the user's taste vector and the movie's property vector. This also includes solving for the rating formula model\n3. Calculate the error by comparing its guess to the actual rating given by the user (actual rating - predicted rating). If the error is positive, the actual rating was higher than the predicted, so the model needs to adjust its weights upward to have higher predictions.\n4. Update the weights accordingly to reduce the error. The model uses the learning rate to slightly tweak the numbers in the matrices. It also applies regularization to ensure the model doesn't change the weights too much just to fit one specific user.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"class MatrixFactorization:\n\n    def __init__(self, n_factors=20, lr=0.01, reg=0.1, n_epochs=20, random_state=42):\n        \"\"\"\n        Parameters\n        \n        n_factors: number of latent factors (embed size, int)\n        lr: learning rate, reduces error for SGD (float)\n        reg: L2 regularization strength, prevents overfitting (lambda, float)\n        n_epochs: number of loops over training data (int)\n        random_state: seed for reproducibility (int)\n        \"\"\"\n        self.n_factors = n_factors\n        self.lr = lr\n        self.reg = reg\n        self.n_epochs = n_epochs\n        self.random_state = random_state\n\n    def fit(self, train_df):\n        \"\"\"\n        Parameters\n\n        train_df: pd.DataFrame with columns ['userId', 'movieId', 'rating']\n\n        Process\n\n        1. Map the given user IDs to matrix rows\n        2. Initialize latent user factors with small random values\n        3. Initialize latent item factors with genre-aware values\n        4. Initialize user and item bias, and the global mean of training set ratings\n\n\n        Predicted rating: mu + b_u + b_i + p_u · q_i\n        \n        \"\"\"\n        np.random.seed(self.random_state)\n\n        self.user_ids = train_df[\"userId\"].unique()\n        self.item_ids = train_df[\"movieId\"].unique()\n        self.user_idx = {u: i for i, u in enumerate(self.user_ids)}\n        self.item_idx = {m: i for i, m in enumerate(self.item_ids)}\n\n        self.user_counts = train_df['userId'].value_counts().to_dict()\n        \n        n_users = len(self.user_ids)\n        n_items = len(self.item_ids)\n\n        count = train_df['movieId'].value_counts()\n        max_c = count.max() if not count.empty else 1\n        self.pop_vector = np.array([count.get(m,0)/max_c for m in self.item_ids])\n\n        self.P = np.random.normal(0, 0.1, (n_users, self.n_factors))\n        if genre_df_onehot is not None:\n            genre_matrix = genre_df_onehot.reindex(self.item_ids).fillna(0).values\n            # Pad or truncate to match n_factors\n            n_genres = genre_matrix.shape[1]\n            if n_genres < self.n_factors:\n                padding = np.random.normal(0, 0.01, (n_items, self.n_factors - n_genres))\n                self.Q = np.hstack([genre_matrix, padding])\n            else:\n                self.Q = genre_matrix[:, :self.n_factors].astype(float)\n        else:\n            self.Q = np.random.normal(0, 0.1, (n_items, self.n_factors))\n\n        if genre_df_onehot is not None:\n            high_ratings = train_df[train_df['rating']>=4.0]\n            for u_i, group in high_ratings.groupby('userId'):\n                if u_i in self.user_idx:\n                    u_index = self.user_idx[u_i]\n                    m_index = [self.item_idx[m] for m in group['movieId'] if m in self.item_idx]\n                    if m_index:\n                        self.P[u_index] = self.Q[m_index].mean(axis=0)\n\n        self.global_mean = train_df[\"rating\"].mean()\n        self.bu = np.zeros(n_users)\n        self.bi = np.zeros(n_items)\n\n\n        \"\"\"\n        SGD Training Loop\n\n        Process\n\n        1. Randomize the order of the ratings\n        2. Initialize epoch_sq_err to track how far off the guesses are, for RMSE\n        3. Call the information of a user, calculate the predicted rating\n                predicted rating: mu + b_u + b_i + p_u · q_i\n        4. Square error, so negative values become positive + add to the running total\n        5. Update biases and latent factors\n                Includes L2 regularization to prevent overfitting\n        6. Calculate average error (once loop ends)\n        \n        \n        \"\"\"\n        records = train_df[[\"userId\", \"movieId\", \"rating\"]].values\n        self.train_rmse_history = []\n\n        for epoch in range(self.n_epochs):\n            neg_records = []\n            sample_size = min(len(records)*2,50000)\n            random_u = np.random.choice(self.user_ids, size=sample_size//2)\n            \n            for u in random_u:\n                random_i = np.random.choice(self.item_ids)\n                neg_records.append([u,random_i,2.5])\n            \n            total_records = np.vstack([records, np.array(neg_records)])\n            np.random.shuffle(total_records)\n            epoch_sq_err = 0.0\n\n            # progress bar tqdm\n            progress_bar = tqdm(records, desc=f\"Epoch {epoch + 1}/{self.n_epochs}\", leave=False)\n\n            for userId, movieId, rating in progress_bar:\n                u = self.user_idx.get(userId)\n                i = self.item_idx.get(movieId)\n                if u is None or i is None:\n                    continue\n\n                pred = (\n                    self.global_mean\n                    + self.bu[u]\n                    + self.bi[i]\n                    + self.P[u] @ self.Q[i]\n                )\n\n                # calculate error + add to total\n                err = rating - pred\n                epoch_sq_err += err ** 2\n\n                # update biases + latent factors\n                self.bu[u] += self.lr * (err - self.reg * self.bu[u])\n                self.bi[i] += self.lr * (err - self.reg * self.bi[i])\n\n                p_u_old = self.P[u].copy()\n                self.P[u] += self.lr * (err * self.Q[i] - self.reg * self.P[u])\n                self.Q[i] += self.lr * (err * p_u_old  - self.reg * self.Q[i])\n\n            epoch_rmse = np.sqrt(epoch_sq_err / len(total_records))\n            self.train_rmse_history.append(epoch_rmse)\n            print(f\"Epoch {epoch + 1:>3}/{self.n_epochs}  Train RMSE: {epoch_rmse:.4f}\")\n\n            self.lr *=0.9\n\n        return self\n\n    def predict(self, userId, movieId):\n        \"\"\"\n        Predict the rating a user would give a movie. This method helps to fill in the blanks\n            for the sparse matrix. We run this for every single movie, then later sort the ratings\n        and find the top-10 recommendations for a specific user.\n\n        Process\n\n        1. Get user ID\n        2. If user/movie not in training set, the model has no latent vectors or biases for it,\n            so fall back to the global mean (baseline, addresses the cold-start problem)\n        3. Calculate rating prediction\n        \n        \"\"\"\n        u = self.user_idx.get(userId)\n        i = self.item_idx.get(movieId)\n\n        if u is None or i is None:\n            return self.global_mean\n\n        return (\n            self.global_mean\n            + self.bu[u]\n            + self.bi[i]\n            + self.P[u] @ self.Q[i]\n        )\n\n    def predict_all(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Predicts all user=movie pariings ratings by dotting P adn Q\n        \"\"\"\n        latent_scores = self.P @ self.Q.T\n\n        n_users = len(self.user_ids)\n        n_items = len(self.item_ids)\n        \n        preds = np.zeros((n_users, n_items))\n        for u in range(n_users) :\n            for i in range(n_items):\n                preds[u][i] = self.global_mean + self.bu[u] + self.bi[i] + latent_scores[u][i]\n\n        return preds\n\n    def recommend_top_k(self, userId, all_movie_ids, seen_movie_ids, k=10):\n        \"\"\"\n        Return the top-k UNSEEN movie recommendations for a user--a list of sorted\n            descending (movieId, predicted_rating) tuples.\n\n        Parameters\n        \n        userId: target user\n        all_movie_ids: iterable of all movie IDs in the dataset\n        seen_movie_ids: set of movies the user has already rated (will be excluded)\n        k: number of k-recommendations (default 10)\n\n        Process\n\n        1. Filter through every movie in the database that a specific user has not seen.\n        2. Calculate the predicted ratings for each unseen movie for that user. Gain a list\n            of all the returned scores from the predict method.\n        3. Sort the scores from highest to lowest.\n        4. Return the top-k recommendations to show to the user. In this project, we use the\n            top 10 scores as our highest movie recommendations.\n        \"\"\"\n        u_index = self.user_idx.get(userId)\n        if u_index is None:\n            unseen_pop = [m for m in all_movie_ids if m in self.item_idx and m not in seen_movie_ids]\n            unseen_pop_score = [(m,self.pop_vector[self.item_idx[n]]) for n in unseen_pop]\n            unseen_pop_score.sort(key=lambda x:x[1],reverse=True)\n            return unseen_pop_score[:k]\n        \n        mf_score = (\n            self.global_mean\n            +self.bu[u_index]\n            +self.bi\n            +(self.P[u_index] @ self.Q.T)\n        )\n\n        user_rate_count = self.user_counts.get(userId,0)\n\n        if user_rate_count<5:\n            mf = 0.5\n            pop = 0.5\n        else:\n            mf = 0.7\n            pop = 0.3\n            \n\n        blended_scores = (mf * mf_score) + (pop * self.pop_vector)\n        \n        unseen = [self.item_idx[m] for m in all_movie_ids if m in self.item_idx and m not in seen_movie_ids]\n        unseen_score = blended_scores[unseen]\n        unseen_m_i = [self.item_ids[u] for u in unseen]\n        scores = list(zip(unseen_m_i,unseen_score))\n        scores.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)\n        return scores[:k]","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.804661Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.804916Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.83372Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.804892Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.832754Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 7. Training","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# initilze model\nmodel = MatrixFactorization(\n    n_factors=20,\n    lr=0.005,\n    reg=0.05,\n    n_epochs=20,\n)\n\n# train model on training data\nmodel.fit(train_df)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.834784Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.835059Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-19T04:53:22.610547Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-19T04:52:39.835006Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-19T04:53:22.609695Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def plot_training_curve(model):\n    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))\n    plt.plot(range(1, len(model.train_rmse_history) + 1), model.train_rmse_history, \n             marker=\"o\", color=\"steelblue\", markersize=4)\n    plt.title(\"MF Training Curve\")\n    plt.xlabel(\"Epoch\")\n    plt.ylabel(\"Train RMSE\")\n